## The God of Work

**Zenithar** is the Divine of work, commerce, and communication. Patron of merchants, artisans, and all those who earn an honest living through the effort of their hands or the sweat of their brow, he embodies the dignity of labor and the value of productivity. Among the **Divines**, Zenithar is perhaps the most pragmatic, teaching that piety is demonstrated through concrete deeds rather than contemplation.

In the cosmology of the **Dawn Era**, Zenithar is often associated with the concept of constructive transformation. Where **Lorkhan** proposed the creation of the world and **Magnus** drew up its plans, Zenithar is said to have embodied the very principle of the labor necessary to bring **Mundus** into being. His contribution is that of the divine toil that transforms idea into reality.

## Doctrines and Teachings

Zenithar's central teaching is simple yet profound: honest work is the highest form of devotion. His faithful believe that every well-made object, every fair transaction, and every day of conscientious labor constitutes a silent prayer to the god of commerce.

Zenithar teaches that prosperity is not a sin but a legitimate reward for effort. Unlike the ascetics of other cults, Zenithar's priests encourage the accumulation of wealth as long as it results from honest work and fair commercial practices. Greed and deceit are the only true commercial sins.

Zenithar's most celebrated precept is often summarized as: "Work brings prosperity, and prosperity enables charity." This virtuous chain links individual effort to collective well-being, justifying commerce as a service rendered to the community.

## Temples and Merchant Guilds

Temples of Zenithar function as much as centers of business as they do as places of worship. They often house sanctified markets, fair-rate lending banks, and commercial arbitration offices. Zenithar's priests serve as mediators in commercial disputes and as guarantors of good faith in transactions.

The Merchants Guild, though officially secular, maintains close ties with the cult of Zenithar. Commercial oaths are often sworn upon his symbol, the anvil, and the most important contracts are blessed by his priests to ensure their good-faith execution.

Artisan guilds — from blacksmiths to weavers to cabinetmakers — place their workshops under Zenithar's protection. Every forge, every workbench, and every loom is considered a miniature altar dedicated to the god of work.

## Zenithar Across Different Cultures

For **Imperials**, Zenithar is naturally associated with the Empire's commercial power. Trade routes, Imperial markets, and the monetary system are all considered manifestations of Zenithar's blessing. Imperial merchants invoke his name before every commercial journey.

Among the **Nords**, Zenithar is known as Tsun, a more martial aspect associated with the concept of trial and merit. For Nords, work is inseparable from the fight against the elements and survival in a hostile environment, which colors their interpretation of the god.

The **Bretons** of High Rock maintain a developed cult of Zenithar, integrating his influence into their tradition of magical craftsmanship. Breton enchanters regard their art as the perfect fusion of manual work and magic, a dual blessing from Zenithar and **Julianos**.

The **Redguards** associate Zenithar with their tradition of excellence in bladesmithing. The curved swords of the Alik'r are considered the pinnacle of martial and artisanal art, worthy of the blessing of the god of work.

## The Blessing of Zenithar

Receiving Zenithar's blessing is said to improve the faithful's artisanal and commercial skills. Blessed merchants negotiate better prices, smiths forge stronger weapons, and miners discover richer veins. This practical blessing explains the cult's popularity among the laboring classes.

Shrines of Zenithar are found in most cities and villages of Tamriel. They are often located near markets or artisan quarters, accessible to those beginning their working day. A quick prayer at dawn before the symbol of the anvil is a daily ritual for many workers.

## Zenithar and the Economy of Tamriel

Zenithar's influence on Tamriel's economy goes beyond simple individual blessing. His cult has contributed to the establishment of commercial standards, systems of weights and measures, and codes of merchant conduct throughout the Empire. Laws against fraud and counterfeiting are often inspired by his precepts.

The East Empire Company, despite its sometimes questionable practices, invoked Zenithar in its founding charters. This tension between the ideal of fair commerce preached by Zenithar and the reality of commercial practices in Tamriel is a recurring theme in the continent's economic literature.

## Opposition and Conflicts

Zenithar stands naturally opposed to laziness and dishonesty, but his primary cosmic antagonist is more subtle. The **Daedric Princes** who offer power without effort, such as **Clavicus Vile** with his deceptive bargains, represent everything Zenithar rejects. The shortcut is the antithesis of his teaching: true value can only arise from sincere work.

Thieves and swindlers are considered blasphemers by Zenithar's faithful. Not only do they take without producing, but they undermine the trust that is the foundation of all commerce. The Thieves Guild is viewed as an abomination by the most devoted followers of the god of work.
